<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="144" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1679,2066]" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,736,1679,1705]" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">
Scanning electron microscopy (
<figureCitation box="[561,692,1679,1705]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 58–65</figureCitation>
):—
</emphasis>
Rapheless valve (SV) (
<figureCitation box="[993,1125,1679,1706]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 58–62</figureCitation>
): Valve surface with shallow, rounded to irregularly shaped depressions along the apical axis, mainly concentrated in the central area (
<figureCitation box="[1308,1440,1715,1742]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 58–60</figureCitation>
). Externally, striae multiseriate, composed of three to five rows of small same-sized round areolae (
<figureCitation box="[1235,1367,1751,1778]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 58–60</figureCitation>
). Striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (
<figureCitation box="[839,971,1787,1814]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 58–59</figureCitation>
). Internally, cavum covered by a hood with a narrow aperture towards the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[571,702,1823,1850]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 61, 62</figureCitation>
). Raphe valve (RV) (
<figureCitation box="[939,1071,1823,1850]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–65" captionStartId="5.[136,243,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[238,1357,190,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@5.[228,1359,190,1773]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–65. SEM. Planothidium marganaiensis G.G.Lai, Ector &amp; C.E.Wetzel sp. nov. Type population from the San Giovanni spring, Sardinia (Italy). Figs 58–62: Rapheless valve (SV). Figs 58–60: External view showing depressions along the apical axis and multiseriate striae. Note the striae continuing shortly onto the valve mantle, without interruption (Figs 58–59). Figs 61–62: Internal view showing the round cavum with a narrow aperture towards the valve mantle. Figs 63–65: Raphe valve (RV). Fig. 63: External view showing multiseriate striae not extended on the valve mantle and distal raphe ends bent unilaterally. Figs 64–65: Internal view showing striae sunken between raised virgae and composed of areolae covered by individual hymenes. Note the proximal external raphe ends slightly deflected into opposite sides and distal raphe terminating on poorly developed helictoglossae, continuing shortly onto the valve mantle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5756796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5756796/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="144">Figs 63–65</figureCitation>
