<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="146" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,1452,158,436]" pageId="6" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,356,302,328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="146">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The name refers to the 
<emphasis box="[612,723,303,328]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="146">Marganai</emphasis>
massif where the karst spring San Giovanni originates. Marganai (Marganái) (Iglesias)—It is an elongated mountain or a mountain of a small mountain chain: it is likely that its name is to be compared—not derived—with Lat. margo, -inis “margin” (Indo-European). Cfr. Marghine (Source: 
<bibRefCitation author="Pittau, M." pageId="6" pageNumber="146" refId="ref9923" refString="Pittau, M. (2013) Toponimi della Sardegna Meridionale. Significato e origine. [http: // www. pittau. it / Sardo / top _ sard _ meridionale. html]" type="url" year="2013">Pittau, 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
